WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.480
Welcome Andrie de Vries Earlier this year, in about February and

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:16.719
March, we sat down with much of the company and said, what kind of use cases do you have

00:00:16.719 --> 00:00:17.719
for AI?

00:00:17.719 --> 00:00:19.719
What would you like to do?

00:00:19.719 --> 00:00:26.280
And many examples came up, and I discovered, much to my delight, that in several use cases

00:00:26.280 --> 00:00:32.480
I could write a really compelling proof-of-concept in about 20 lines of code using ellmer or

00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:36.240
Ragnar or whatever I used at the time.

00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:41.459
My audience loved it, typically I would then take that proof-of-concept and build it into

00:00:41.459 --> 00:00:49.040
a shiny app, I would use ellmer to speak to the LLM and to write maybe some DuckDB code

00:00:49.040 --> 00:00:56.000
and that code will query information from a database and present it back to the user.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.040
Everybody loved this and I then carried on and made more complicated apps using multiple

00:01:01.040 --> 00:01:04.639
data sources and this unlocked an immense amount of value.

00:01:04.639 --> 00:01:11.160
Imagine one of my apps that combines information from our Salesforce database and Zendesk tickets

00:01:11.160 --> 00:01:18.040
and multiple other data sources and now a sales rep or anybody else can query information

00:01:18.040 --> 00:01:22.879
in one place that previously would have been very, very difficult to go and do and they

00:01:22.879 --> 00:01:25.480
just didn't do that.

00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:31.440
This was great until InfoSec heard about this.

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:35.080
You've had the same problem.

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:39.239
My name is Andri, I'm director of product strategy at Posit and I'm going to talk a

00:01:39.239 --> 00:01:45.480
little bit about how I worked with InfoSec to get to a happy place that everybody was

00:01:45.480 --> 00:01:47.320
okay with.

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:53.839
So InfoSec, information security, they care about three things, apparently this is the

00:01:53.839 --> 00:02:03.279
oath they swear to be inducted in the hall of fame of InfoSec agents, I guess.

00:02:03.279 --> 00:02:06.720
Confidentiality, integrity and availability.

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:08.559
Availability means does this app run?

00:02:08.559 --> 00:02:12.919
Is it available six sigma, 99.99%?

00:02:12.919 --> 00:02:19.919
I let them deal with that but I need to be much more aware of confidentiality so if I

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:25.800
surface new information, is the person that views that information, are they authorised

00:02:25.800 --> 00:02:26.800
to see that?

00:02:26.800 --> 00:02:33.919
And integrity, in other words, is this information accurate and can it be trusted?

00:02:33.919 --> 00:02:41.919
So if I have an LNM app, InfoSec flags a number of risks and I'm going to highlight three

00:02:41.919 --> 00:02:43.000
of them.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.559
You need to work with your own team to see what's relevant for you.

00:02:47.559 --> 00:02:52.559
The first one is the risk of data leakage, in other words, if I combine information from

00:02:52.559 --> 00:03:00.320
multiple sources, all of which has potentially sensitive information like PII, personally

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:08.320
identifiable information or trade secrets, you run the risk of grabbing information from

00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:12.479
multiple places, combining that together and then accidentally surfacing that to somebody

00:03:12.479 --> 00:03:17.119
who should not have had access to that.

00:03:17.119 --> 00:03:23.119
The second risk was, well, what if I use an LNM to generate some data and it makes

00:03:23.119 --> 00:03:27.800
up some nonsense and I write that back into a production database?

00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:29.399
Nobody wants that.

00:03:29.399 --> 00:03:36.399
But you also want to have this balance about keeping data in a sandbox, not creating data

00:03:36.399 --> 00:03:37.399
silos.

00:03:37.399 --> 00:03:41.399
So there's a risk that InfoSec is going to want to speak to you about that.

00:03:41.399 --> 00:03:45.160
And the third one is a little bit more subtle but everybody is concerned about this.

00:03:45.199 --> 00:03:51.360
If I'm using an LNM agent, and you can use your agent of choice, there is a small risk

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:58.000
that if you don't control for this carefully, that the data, that your own data will be

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:03.960
used for training and can accidentally leak to other users, not just on the same server

00:04:03.960 --> 00:04:07.880
but also if it's retrained in the future.

00:04:07.880 --> 00:04:12.360
I'm not going to pretend that the solutions I have here is going to work for you.

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:15.520
But here are a few things to go and think about.

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:21.119
First of all, make sure that your authorization is correct, that you give minimal permissions,

00:04:21.119 --> 00:04:24.959
so you limit your app to trusted users.

00:04:24.959 --> 00:04:29.920
Make sure that you have data security of the LNM itself.

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:34.640
In our case, we host our models on AWS Bedrock.

00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:40.040
Most of the cloud providers have a service like that where they ensure that your data

00:04:40.119 --> 00:04:44.760
will not leak out and will not be used for retraining.

00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:45.760
And scope to mission.

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:50.600
So if you write information somewhere else, make sure that where you write it to has the

00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:55.079
same permissions and authorization you had before.

00:04:55.079 --> 00:04:58.679
In short, don't ask for forgiveness.

00:04:58.679 --> 00:05:04.839
Ask for permission and ask it early, as soon as you know that you are going to be touching

00:05:04.839 --> 00:05:07.839
sensitive information.

00:05:07.839 --> 00:05:10.839
Thank you.

